<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>8 December 2013_x000b_Jane Bickerstaffe, Director, INCPEN</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by The Industry Council for Research on Packaging and the Environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (INCPEN)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">INCPEN is a research body established in 1974 to consider the environmental and social impacts of packaging. INCPEN members represent all stages of the supply chain. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> It is INCPEN’s view that the proposed charge on carrier bags in England will have no beneficial impact on the environment. Worse, the proposed exemption for biodegradable bags will result in the closure of UK plastics reprocessing with consequent job losses.  It will also give a very confusing message to consumers. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">It will not reduce litter or save resources and will impact disproportionately on poorer people who have to use public transport and will still need bags to take their shopping home. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introducing a bag levy for no other reason than to address what some have described as ‘an iconic symbol of our consumer society’ is unjustified and ill advised. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> If that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">were a valid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">reason </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">for a levy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> should presumably </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">appl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> to all other symbols such as mobile phones and trainers.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">When first proposed the bag levy was claimed as a litter reduction measure, but in reality carrier bags are not a significant part of litter accounting for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">0.03% (source Keep Britain Tidy litter count 2008).</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In 2010, e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ight years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> after the introduction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of a levy on plastic carrier bags in Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> bags of all kinds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(not just thin plastic ones) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">constituted just 0.25% of litter (compared to 0.22% in 2002) according to the Irish Litter Monitoring Body. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is no evidence that the antisocial practice of dropping litter is impacted by such a levy and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">here is no correlation between the number of bags used and the number that get littered.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">An exemption for biodegradable bags will have a number of negative impacts. If gives a misleading, confusing message to the public.  Whether a material degrades or not is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">relevant to its environmental impact – paper degrades, glass is inert; neither is better than the other.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Large amounts of regular plastics carrier bags are currently recycled to make polythene film. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It will not be possible to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> keep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">biodegradable or oxo-degradable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> separate from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">regular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> plastic bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  Even a very small amount contaminates the regular plastic and means it cannot be recycled because quality of the finished product would be jeopardised.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s will bring an end to UK reprocess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing of plastics bags, further reducing the decline in UK manufacturing and resulting in UK job losses.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Biodegradable, compostable bags are typically as much as 7 times more expensive than regular thin plastic bags.  Oxo-degradable bags are closer in price to regular ones so it is inevitable that manufacturers will switch to oxo-degradable bags. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">These bags, in common with all regular plastic bags, will be manufactured in the Far East.  All bag manufacture moved to the Far East over 10 years ago because raw material and manufacturing costs are much cheaper than European. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">oxo-degradable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">addi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tive is produced in the USA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is not likely to be any reduction in the amount of plastic film produced as a result of a levy.  To the contrary, it is likely that greater volumes of heavier plastic film will be used to manufacture heavier ‘Bags for Life’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. More tailor-made bin liner bags and bags for other purposes will be purchased by people who currently re-use traditional bags for these purposes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In 2011 the UK Environment Agency carried out a </span><a href="http://a0768b4a8a31e106d8b0-50dc802554eb38a24458b98ff72d550b.r19.cf3.rackcdn.com/scho0711buan-e-e.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">major study</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of supermarket carrier bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Life cycle assessment of supermarket carrier bags: a review of the bags available in 2006</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that concluded a thin plastic bag does least damage to the environment of any carrier bag and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an environmentally responsible way for consumers to carry their groceries home.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The EA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">study found that natural-fibre bags made from cotton would have to be used more than 131 times in order to have the same low impact. Paper bags would have to be reused 3 times to match the performance of thin plastic. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The levy on plastic carrier bags in Ireland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">had a net negative environmental effect.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> It resulted in more lorries on the roads (to deliver heavier alternative types of bags to shops) and more plastic being used as sales of tailor-made bags for bin liners and other purposes replaced the carriers. Statistics published by HM Customs and Excise show the amount of all types of plastic bags and sacks used in Ireland in 2001 (before the levy) was 29.8 thousand tonnes and in 2006 it had increased to 31.6 thousand tonnes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">restriction on carrier bags is not justified on environmental grounds, given that the EA study found that it was the least bad option. Trying to compare the ‘advantages’ and ‘disadvantages’ of the proposed levy is meaningless, and suggesting as an alternative a complete ban on lightweight carrier bags is clearly environmentally negative and disproportionately hard on the poor.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It makes no sense to compare bag levies and bans introduced in other countries, such as Bangladesh, where plastics of all types can block drains and river courses. Those countries lack the UK’s efficient waste collection and disposal services. The best solution in such countries is not to ban one type of material but to introduce western-style waste management practices.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Nor does it make any sense to impose additional costs on families already struggling in the tough economic climate. They will still need to get their shopping home, wrap used nappies and other smelly waste before disposal, line rubbish bins etc.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Instead of reusing free thin bags  - which 80% of households do according to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> DEFRA/WRAP study </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">conducted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">IPSOS MORI in 2007 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">- they will now have to buy new bags specifically for these tasks.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It also seems unfair to place the burden of administering a levy scheme on local authorities which are already hard-pressed. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is a very easy way to reduce the environmental impact, small though it is, of getting shopping home. Consumers simply need to take their own bags and keep reusing them either for shopping again, bin liners or other purposes.  If they need more bags then shops, as they do now, can make a range available.  Shop staff can help by asking customers if they really need a bag or can add thei</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r shopping to a bag they already have. This would have no administrative and enforcement costs and was enable consumers to choose the least harmful environmental option.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">INCPEN would welcome the opportunity to supplement this with oral evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">8 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>